North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the extension of sanctions deepens distrust of the United States and that under such circumstances the country will in no way be able to give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual UN General Assembly that North Korea had taken “substantial goodwill measures” last year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site, and committing not to spread nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not see a corresponding reaction from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances we will in no way be the first to disarm unilaterally.”
And while Ri echoed North Korea’s familiar complaints about Washington’s opposition to a “step-by-step” approach to denuclearization that would reward North Korea for incremental steps, his statement turned out to be important in that it did not reject Pyongyang’s unilateral denuclearization in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between the current US president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim called for work to "denuclearize the Korean Peninsula" and Trump promised security guarantees to North Korea.
North Korea seeks a formal end to the 1950-1953 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington is also resisting calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘denuclearisation first’ and raises the level of pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal by force, and even objects to ‘declaring the end of the war,’” he said.
“To believe that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an impossible dream for those who do not know us.
But the problem is that the extension of sanctions deepens our distrust.”
Ree did not mention the plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US leader stressed at the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister drew attention to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: "If South Korea, and not the United States, were a party to this issue of denuclearization, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have come to such a dead end."
Despite this, the tone of Ree's speech was sharply different from last year's when he told the General Assembly that targeting North Korea's missiles at the U.S. mainland was inevitable after "Mr. Wicked President" Trump called Kim a "rocket man" who wants to commit suicide.
At the United Nations this year, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking disarmament measures, but said much more needs to be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea’s denuclearization.
On Wednesday, Trump said that he does not set a time frame for this: “It will take two years, three years or five months — it does not matter.”
