"She told me that no one ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," a teacher from The Telegraph shared.
At the course, which was first introduced this year, students are taught the basics of how good sleep habits help to achieve academic and sports results, as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's medical services, said the university decided to introduce the course after it was found that students were seriously sleep-deprived within a week.
The hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a room in a dormitory where students click cups of coffee, curtains, exercisers, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, the effects of sleep deficit on athletic performance, and the importance of sleep-related routines.
In another section, participants are told how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Next, a campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not change the behavior of students instantly.
