Tim Berners-Lee, inventor of the world wide web, is launching a new startup to create competition between Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the legend of the world of technology, Inrupt, is developing an open source platform Solid, the idea of which belongs to Berners-Lee.
With the Solid platform, users will be able to choose where to store data and whom to give access to this or that information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that Inrupt's goal was "world domination."
“We have to do it now,” he said of the startup.
This is a historic moment.”
The application uses Solid technology, which will allow users to create a "personal online data repository" or POD.
It can store lists of contacts, lists of current cases, calendar, audio library and other tools for own use and work.
It’s like using Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify in the same browser at the same time.
The unique feature of this personal online data storage is that it fully meets the needs of the user who can access any information.
The company calls it "extending personal capabilities with data."
According to Inrupt CEO John Bruce, the company aims to leverage resources, processes, and relevant skills to make the Solid platform available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform acquired from IBM, several full-time developers hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world can create their own stand-alone applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not in talks with Facebook and Google about whether to make a full replacement when all their business models undergo fundamental changes in a short period of time.
"We don't ask for their permission."
Berners-Lee wrote in a Medium post on Saturday that Inrupt’s mission is “to provide commercial energy and ecosystem and help protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on the Solid platform.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet by founding the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential figure in the debate over net neutrality.
Even at the time of Inrupt's launch, Berners-Lee remained the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, The Web Foundation, and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m very optimistic about the next era of the web,” Berners-Lee added.
Bernard Vann: celebrations on the occasion of the presentation of the representative of the Church of the Order of the Victoria Cross during the First World War
The only representative of the Church of England, who received the Order of the Victoria Cross for participation in hostilities during the First World War, is honored in his hometown 100 years later.
Lt. Col. Bernard Vann received an award for his part in the attack under Belanglis and Leokur on 29 September 1918.
However, he was killed by a sniper bullet four days later and never found out that he received the highest military award in Britain.
On Saturday, two of his grandchildren unveiled the memorial stone during a parade in the town of Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of his grandchildren, Michael Vann, called “extremely symbolic” that the discovery of the memorial stone occurred exactly 100 years after his grandfather performed the feat for which he received the award.
According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Vann moved his battalion across the St. Caten Canal "through a very thick fog and under dense fire of field guns and machine guns."
Later, he rushed to the firing line and with "desperate courage" led the line forward, before this one broke through to the field gun and destroyed three guns of the enemy unit.
Lt. Col. Vann was shot dead by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just over a month before the war ended.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather had done something he himself would never have been able to repeat and that he deserved respect.
He and his brother Dr. James Vann laid a wreath after a parade led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said he was "very proud to take part in this parade" and added that "the courage of a true hero is shown by the respect that so many people show him."
