Federal prosecutors demand rare death penalty for New York terror suspect
In New York, federal prosecutors are demanding the death penalty for Saifullo Saipov, a suspected terrorist attack in New York City that killed eight people, a rare punishment not applied in the state for a federal crime since 1953.
In October, the 30-year-old Saipov drove a Home Depot-leased pickup truck onto a bicycle path along a highway in the West Side, Lower Manhattan, and began beating down cyclists and pedestrians that happened to him on the way.
According to a report of intent to seek execution filed in the Southern District of New York to justify the death penalty, prosecutors must prove that Saipov "intentionally" killed eight people and "intentionally" caused serious bodily harm.
According to court materials, each of these charges provides for the possibility of the death penalty.
A few weeks after the attack, the Federal jury charged Saipov with 22 counts, including eight counts of murder for the purpose of extortion, which are usually brought by federal prosecutors in cases related to organized crime, as well as charges of violence and destruction of motor vehicles.
According to the prosecutors, who described the crime committed by Saipov as “horrible, cruel and malicious”, this attack is the result of “careful planning and premeditated intent.”
The victims that Saifulla Habibullaevich Saipov injured, harmed or killed were Diego Enrique Angelini, Nicolas Cleves, Ann-Laura Decadt, Darren Drake, Ariel Erlich, Hernan Ferruchi, Hernan Diego Mendoza and Alejandro Damian Pagnucco, as described in the intent report.
Five of the dead were tourists from Argentina.
It has been ten years since the last time a criminal case was opened in the Southern District of New York, which is punishable by the death penalty.
The defendant, Khalid Barnes, was found guilty of murdering two drug suppliers, and eventually sentenced to life in prison in September 2009.
The last time the death penalty on a federal case was carried out in New York in 1953. The married couple Julius and Ethel Rosenberg were executed after being convicted of conspiracy to spy for the Soviet Union during the Cold War two years earlier.
Both Rosenbergs were executed in an electric chair on June 19, 1953.
According to court materials, Saipov, a native of Uzbekistan, did not show remorse in the days and months following the attack.
According to police, he told investigators that he did not regret what he had done.
According to the indictment, Saipov told authorities that he was inspired to carry out an attack by an ISIS video he was watching on his phone.
The police report that he also asked to hang the flag of ISIS in his hospital room.
He pleaded not guilty to 22 counts.
David Patton, one of the federal public defenders representing Saipov, said they were "very disappointed" by the prosecutor's decision.
“We believe that the decision to seek the death penalty, instead of admitting guilt and sentencing to life imprisonment without the possibility of release, will only exacerbate the psychological trauma caused by these events for all victims,” Patton said.
The defense side of Saipov earlier also asked the accusers not to seek the death penalty.
