How a trade war between the U.S. and China could benefit Beijing
Experts believe that the first steps in the trade war between the United States and China were desperate, and, although it is far from over, in the long term, the split between the countries can benefit Beijing.
U.S. President Donald Trump fired the first warning shots earlier this year, taxing major Chinese exports, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The worst of the situation has escalated this week due to new tariffs on goods with a total value of $ 200 billion (150 billion pounds), which actually imposes a tax on half of all goods coming to the United States from China.
Beijing has paid back the same coin each time, recently imposing a duty of five to ten percent on $60 billion worth of American goods.
China has pledged to take similar measures to the United States, and the world's second largest economy is unlikely to miss the opportunity to keep this promise in the near future.
Forcing Washington to back down means accepting the demands, but for Chinese President Xi Jinping, U.S. public worship is too shameful.
However, if Beijing makes the right use of the situation, the pressure in the trade war with the United States can bring China an advantage in the long term, reducing the relationship between the two economies.
"A quick political decision in Washington or Beijing could create conditions that lead to a sharp economic fall in any of the countries. And this actually poses a greater threat than observers have previously recognized," said Abigail Grace, an analyst who deals with Asia-related issues at the think tank Center for New American Security.
